items.title: IBM-Swift/Kitura#782 Add @discardableResult
items.body:
`RouterResponse.render()` lacks a `@discardableResult` annotation.

This means that `try response.render("data", context: ["name": "George"])` gives this warning:

`warning: result of call to 'render(_:context:)' is unused`

items.title: Avoid converting JSON serialized Data to String and back to Data again.
items.body:
## Description

Improve Kitura's JSON output performance, by having SwiftyJSON serialize the JSON object as a Data struct directly, rather than a String. This avoids a conversion from Data to String and then a conversion from String to Data.
## Motivation and Context

Help with issue 788
## How Has This Been Tested?

Kitura Unit tests passed on Linux and macOS.

items.title: Added favicon for static resources, web browsers on Linux intermittently cannot find favicon
items.body:
## Description
I ran into an issue using Chrome on Linux to run some selenium tests. My tests would run through multiple Kitura routes I have created and every 5/6 network requests to these routes, I would get the error `Cannot GET /favicon.ico` causing my test to instantly fail. This issue only appears on Linux web browsers (Chrome/Firefox), but works fine on Mac. The fix for this was simply adding a reference to a favicon.ico and all my tests ran perfectly.

## Motivation and Context
It should prevent myself and anyone else from running into this issue. Additionally, its a minor code change that shouldn't affect anything else.

## How Has This Been Tested?
Tested on Ubuntu 14.04 using Google Chrome 54.0.2840.71 64-bit primarily.
Tested with Kitura 1.0.1
I have tested this on Linux and Mac with the fix mentioned above and it worked properly.
I also tested by creating my own `/public` folder at the root of my project. I added an `index.html` and a `favicon.ico` file which ended up giving me the same results as using the default Kitura static resources. Eventually fails with no favicon reference, and everything works with favicon reference.

items.title: Modified MultiPartBodyParser so that it reads a filename if present
items.body:
This modifies `MultiPartBodyParser` so that the `filename` section of `Content-Disposition` is read and stored correctly, if present.

## Description
I've duplicated the existing `MultiPartBodyParser` code to parse `name`, and created a new `filename` property in `Part` also based on `name`. I've also modified the multi-part tests to check filename is parsed correctly.

## Motivation and Context
Content-Disposition can optionally include a `filename` field ([more info](https://developer.mozilla.org/en-US/docs/Web/HTTP/Headers/Content-Disposition)), but this was being ignored by `MultiPartBodyParser`. This change reads and stores `filename` if it's present.

## How Has This Been Tested?
`swift test` passes with no errors. I've modified `testMultipartFormParsing()` to ensure `filename` is being parsed correctly.

## Checklist:
